### Abstract

 This article introduces ThingsBoard Message Queue(TBMQ), a scalable and fault-tolerant Message Queuing Telemetry Transport(MQTT) broker designed to address the challenges of data handling in large-scale Internet of Things(loT) ecosystems.TBMQ's distributed architecture enables horizontal scalability, fault tolerance, and relia-ble data delivery,ensuring high availability and data durability under heavy load condi-tions.The broker efficiently handles two prevalent communication patterns in big data loT applications: the fan-in pattern, where a large number of devices generate high volumes of messages for processing, and the fan-out pattern, where a few requests trigger significant outgoing data to multiple devices. Leveraging Apache Kafka(Kafka),TBMQ supports over 100 million concurrent client connections and a throughput exceeding 3 million messages per second.This paper explores the architectural deci-sions,technical innovations, and strategic use of Kafka, providing insights into building reliable and scalable messaging systems suitable for the demanding requirements of big data in loT.

Keywords: MQTT broker,TBMQ,ThingsBoard

### Introduction

 In the rapidly evolving landscape of the IoT, the demand for MQTT brokers that can effi-ciently manage communication between IoT devices continues to grow. As IoT networks expand, the need for middleware capable of handling high-performance and durable data exchanges becomes increasingly important. Within this context, the ThingsBoard platform has gained prominence as a widely-used open-source IoT platform, receiving considerable attention from the academic community, as evidenced by multiple studies([1-4]).

Recent research, including the systematic mapping study by Di Felice and Paolone(2024)[5], highlights the central role of ThingsBoard within the academic landscape This study identified ThingsBoard as a leading open-source IoT platform, recognized for its extensive features and detailed documentation. By querying the Scopus database and analyzing 55 relevant articles, the authors showcased the broad applicability of Things Board across various domains, reinforcing its versatility for IoT-related projects.

The widespread adoption of ThingsBoard by corporate clients has provided valu able insights into common MQTT application scenarios. These insights helped identify

several key use cases that MQTT brokers need to support efficiently. Based on this expe-rience, it was recognized that existing open-source MQTT brokers often addressed only isolated aspects- such as scalability or protocol support- while lacking a comprehen-sive combination of essential capabilities like horizontal scalability, fault tolerance, data durability, efficient resource utilization, and persistent session support. While over half of the reviewed open-source MQTT brokers support features like shared subscriptions or MQTT 5.0, none of them offer clustering combined with built-in durable message storage in their open-source editions- a critical requirement for large-scale, reliable IoT deployments. These observations are consistent with recent industrial surveys, which highlight that MQTT broker implementations often present trade-offs between perfor-mance, persistence, and deployment flexibility, particularly in cloud-native scenarios[6].

Rather than attempting to adapt existing solutions- many of which rely on monolithic architectures or technology stacks incompatible with ThingsBoard ecosystem the deci-sion was to design TBMQ as a distributed broker built from the ground up. Our goal was to integrate all of these critical capabilities within a single, high-performance open-source solution. This decision allowed us to implement differentiated handling of client types, optimize resource usage, and align the system design with real-world IoT com-munication patterns.

The development of the TBMQ broker began in 2020, aiming to meet these demands,and by 2021, it was integrated into commercial projects. Performance evaluations have demonstrated TBMQ's ability to support 100 million concurrent client connections and process over 3 million messages per second in cluster configurations. Following success-ful production deployments, the TBMQ broker was open-sourced in June 2023. Written in Java and built on established technologies such as Kafka, TBMQ is designed to ensure reliable message delivery between IoT devices and applications while supporting hori-zontal scalability.

### The limitations of existing MQTT brokers

MQTT[7] is a widely used Publish/Subscribe(pub/sub) protocol in IoT systems. An MQTT broker acts as an intermediary to manage the exchange of messages between IoT devices and server-side applications.

Various evaluations have been carried out to assess the performance of IoT brokers,though many of these overlook critical aspects such as data durability and other quali-tative factors. A study by[8] proposes a methodology for classifying and evaluating MQTT brokers, aimed at supporting both the scientific community and the technology industry. This study highlights the importance of improving broker documentation, con-figuration flexibility, and ease of use as key focus areas for broker developers.

One key finding from the study is that while some brokers exhibit efficient algorithms for message delivery, they show inefficiencies in areas like memory allocation and mes-sage queue management. This suggests room for optimization in these aspects.

The MQTT broker comparison presented in[9] provides a detailed overview of the features of various brokers, including protocol-specific properties, security features,cloud deployment options, and data visualization capabilities, as well as a comparison of MQTT client libraries.

Key insights from this comparison include:

● Protocol-Specific Properties: Most MQTT brokers support Quality of Service(QoS)levels, retain flags, Last Will and Testament(LWT), and persistent connection fea-tures. RabbitMQ, however, supports only QoS 0 and 1. About 61.53% of brokers sup-port the shared subscription feature, while 57.14% have adopted MQTT 5.0. Notably,69.23% of brokers have yet to implement MQTT for Sensor Networks(MQTT-SN).

● Security-Related Properties: All the reviewed MQTT brokers provide security fea-tures through authentication, MQTT over Secure Sockets Layer(SSL)/Transport Layer Security(TLS), and WebSocket(WS)/WebSocket Secure(WSS), demonstrat-ing the emphasis on secure communication in broker implementations.

● Cloud and Data Visualization Properties: About 64.28% of brokers support cloud hosting, reflecting a trend toward cloud-based deployments. Furthermore, 85.71%offer Docker container support, indicating a preference for containerization to enhance portability and scalability. Additionally, 92.3% include a User Interface(UI)and dashboard for easier management and monitoring of MQTT operations. How-ever, integration with bare metal environments, ElasticSearch, and Tableau services is still limited.

● MQTT Client Libraries Comparison: The majority of brokers(83.33%) are open-source, which highlights the role of community-driven development within the MQTT ecosystem. The brokers reviewed were implemented using various lan-guages,including C,Java,C++,Python,and Erlang,reflecting the diverse applicabil-ity of MQTT across different technology stacks.

In terms of open-source versus closed-source solutions, nearly 50% of the brokers ana-lyzed are open-source, while the remainder are closed-source[9]. Our analysis focused primarily on the open-source editions of well-known MQTT brokers, as these provide access to source code, allowing for a more in-depth evaluation.

Eclipse Mosquitto, despite being a widely used open-source MQTT broker, does not natively support clustering, limiting its scalability to the capacity of a single server.Although proprietary versions of Mosquitto offer a clustering mechanism where one node serves as a leader and the others as followers, this approach does not fully support horizontal scaling, as the leader node can become a bottleneck for all incoming traffic[10].

HiveMQ is notable for its support of the MQTT 5 protocol and offers a comprehensive dashboard for monitoring broker activity and connections. However, only the commu-nity edition of HiveMQ is open-source, and it lacks features such as clustering, overload protection, and automatic scaling[11].

EMQX is a popular MQTT broker that offers horizontally scalable clustering in its open-source edition, enabled by its masterless distributed architecture. While EMQX community edition supports session takeover and provides node-local durable sessions,these are not replicated across the cluster. This means that persistent session handling and message durability are limited to a single node, posing challenges for high-availabil-ity deployments. Durable session replication and shared storage are available only in the Enterprise Edition[13].

VerneMQ is another significant open-source MQTT broker, designed for high avail-ability and scalability with its Erlang/Open Telecom Platform(OTP)-based architecture.

It supports clustering, enabling horizontal scaling across multiple nodes without a sin-gle point of failure. However, adding or removing nodes within a VerneMQ cluster is not fully automated and requires additional configuration steps, such as using discovery nodes. Additionally, VerneMQ currently lacks a comprehensive web interface for tasks like managing MQTT client credentials or monitoring active connections, which could enhance the user experience[14].

An extensive evaluation of various open-source MQTT brokers, based on criteria such as compatibility, resource consumption, and latency, was conducted in[15]. This study reveals a trade-off between resource usage and latency. Mosquitto, for example, is well-suited for resource-constrained environments due to its low resource requirements,while Erlang-based brokers like EMQX and VerneMQ excel in scenarios with high data throughput and unstable network conditions, despite their higher resource demands.HiveMQ, developed in Java, strikes a balance between performance and functional-ity, making it a suitable option for enterprise applications that require comprehensive MQTT support and integration capabilities.

In summary, while existing open-source MQTT brokers offer valuable features for a variety of IoT scenarios, each has specific limitations in scalability, persistence, or oper-ational flexibility. A recent review of broker architectures confirms that many modern MQTT solutions still trade off performance for durability or cluster flexibility, particu-larly under large-scale conditions[16].

To provide a consolidated view of the capabilities and limitations discussed above,Table 1 presents a comparative summary of the key features of the most widely used open-source MQTT brokers alongside TBMQ.

### Design principles of TBMQ

### Key requirements

The development of TBMQ was guided by a set of design principles aimed at addressing the key requirements of modern IoT and messaging ecosystems. These principles ensure that TBMQ is a scalable and efficient MQTT broker[17].

Scalability: TBMQ is designed to support both vertical and horizontal scalability. This approach allows the system to expand by either adding more resources to existing nodes(vertical) or increasing the number of nodes in the system(horizontal), making it suit-able for managing growing networks of devices and increasing data volumes.

Fault Tolerance: In TBMQ's architecture, every broker node within the cluster is iden-tical, running the same codebase. This uniformity ensures that any node can take over from another without disruption, providing resilience in the event of system failures.

Data Durability: TBMQ emphasizes data durability through its persistence mecha-nisms based on Kafka. MQTT messages and client subscription details are stored redun-dantly across multiple locations, safeguarding against data loss during hardware failures by ensuring critical information is stored in several locations.

Data Compactness: TBMQ uses Protocol Buffers(Protobuf)[18] as the standardized method of communication, which reduces payload sizes and optimizes bandwidth and storage requirements. Protobuf enables backward and forward compatibility, allowing TBMQ to evolve its message formats and data structures, and ensuring seamless cluster

Performance evaluations of binary seriali-zation methods have shown that Protocol Buffers typically produce messages 10-30%smaller and offer serialization speeds up to twice as fast compared to other schema-based binary formats such as Avro, Thrift, or MessagePack[19],[20],[21]. These gains are particularly important in high-throughput clustered environments like TBMQ,where serialization overhead can directly impact system performance and scalability.

Efficiency: TBMQ is capable of efficiently handling millions of clients and process-ing hundreds of thousands of messages per second on a single server node. At scale, a TBMQ cluster supports a throughput of up to 100 million clients and 3 million messages per second, making it suitable for large-scale IoT deployments.

### Core Libraries and Algorithms

TBMQ employs a custom implementation of an actor system inspired by Akka[23],designed to meet its specific requirements. The actor model, a popular approach for distributed systems[24-26], allows TBMQ to manage numerous entities as individual actors,ensuring efficient and concurrent message processing.

Netty[27, 28] was selected for the implementation of the Transmission Control Pro-tocol(TCP) server that manages the MQTT protocol due to its performance and flex-ibility. Recent evaluations[29] have demonstrated that Netty performs well in highly concurrent scenarios, consuming fewer Central Processing Unit(CPU) resources com-pared to other frameworks.

TBMQ optimizes performance through the use of the Trie data structure, which allows for efficient in-memory subscription persistence, enabling rapid access to topic patterns.

### MQTT clients classification

TBMQ categorizes MQTT clients based on their persistence requirements and roles within IoT systems. This classification is informed by our experience with IIoT and large-scale IoT deployments, where millions of devices transmit data to a limited number of applications. These deployments revealed distinct usage patterns between IoT devices and applications, influencing how TBMQ handles message persistence and delivery.

Standard MQTT client(DEVICE) clients, typically representing IoT devices or sen-sors, primarily publish large volumes of data and subscribe to a limited number of topics.Depending on the use case, DEVICE clients may operate in non-persistent mode-suit-able for lightweight, immediate message delivery without persistence-or as persistent clients, where reliable message delivery is critical.

Application(APPLICATION) clients, by contrast, subscribe to data streams from tens or even hundreds of thousands of devices and often serve as back-end processing com-ponents in real-time systems. These clients require reliable message delivery, particularly in scenarios involving downtime caused by maintenance, upgrades, failover events, or network disruptions.

By introducing a clear distinction between DEVICE and APPLICATION clients,TBMQ enables optimized handling of persistent sessions and message delivery strat-egies, ensuring efficient resource utilization, high message throughput, and reliable operation in distributed environments. This classification also forms the basis for the

following discussion on the persistence mechanisms employed in TBMQ, specifically PostgreSQL, Kafka, and Redis.

### PostgreSQL usage

PostgreSQL[34] serves as the primary relational database in TBMQ, used exclusively for storing system metadata and MQTT client credentials rather than MQTT messages.Specifically, PostgreSQL holds critical entities such as user credentials, MQTT client credentials, system statistics, WebSocket sessions, and MQTT subscription records.

Known for its robustness, transactional consistency, and strong ACID guarantees,PostgreSQL ensures the integrity and durability of this metadata. However, it is impor-tant to highlight that TBMQ does not rely on PostgreSQL for high-frequency message processing or real-time session operations. Instead, interactions with PostgreSQL occur primarily during client provisioning, credential validation, or management operations-scenarios where data integrity and transactional safety are essential, but high-through-put performance is not critical.

By restricting PostgreSQL's role to metadata storage, TBMQ avoids introducing a potential performance bottleneck into the message handling pipeline, ensuring scalabil-ity and low latency in real-time operations.

### Redis usage patterns

Redis[35] is a high-performance, in-memory data store that excels in scenarios requir-ing low-latency and high-throughput access, making it well-suited for storing real-time operational data. In TBMQ, Redis plays a key role in two major areas.

First, Redis is used to persist messages for persistent DEVICE clients, ensuring rapid message storage and retrieval. Its ability to handle large datasets in memory, combined with the scalability of Redis Cluster, allows TBMQ to efficiently manage message persis-tence and delivery, even as the number of clients and system load grow. This scalability enables Redis to distribute data across multiple nodes while maintaining consistent per-formance and reliability.

Second, Redis is extensively used as a caching layer for various system operations beyond message persistence. For example, TBMQ caches client credentials, session information, and other frequently accessed metadata in Redis to offload workloads from PostgreSQL. This caching strategy significantly reduces database load, improves access times, and enhances overall system scalability.

The detailed design choices, implementation aspects, and performance evaluation of Redis-based message persistence for DEVICE clients are presented in a separate study,which addresses scalable point-to-point MQTT messaging scenarios in IoT environ-ments[22].

### Kafka usage patterns

Kafka[30, 31] serves as TBMQ's distributed event streaming platform, enabling reliable message dispatch across TBMQ cluster nodes. Kafka's storage system ensures message durability, even under heavy loads, with minimal performance degradation[33]. Kafka is crucial throughout the MQTT workflow, handling client sessions and subscription man-agement. Kafka's role in TBMQ includes:

Message Storage. Upon receiving a PUBLISH message via Netty, TBMQ sends it to the tbmq.msg.all Kafka topic. QoS 0 clients receive immediate MQTT Publish Acknowl-edgment packet(PUBACK), while QoS 1 and 2 clients receive acknowledgment after Kafka confirms message receipt.

Session and Subscription Management: TBMQ manages MQTT sessions and sub-scriptions by pushing client session data to tbmq.client.session and subscription data to tbmq.client.subscriptions Kafka topics. This setup ensures real-time access to client states, enhancing service continuity and scalability.

Persistent Session Optimization with Client Classification. Building on the client clas-sification introduced in Sect. 3.3, TBMQ optimizes message handling and storage strate-gies for each client type to balance performance, scalability, and reliability.

DEVICE clients: TBMQ processes published messages using a shared Kafka topic tbmq.msg.persisted with dedicated Kafka consumers storing the data into Redis,ensuring reliable delivery upon reconnection without assigning dedicated Kafka topics per client. This approach avoids the resources overhead to manage numerous Kafka top-ics while maintaining reliable low-latency delivery. Figure 2 shows the message transmis-sion path for DEVICE clients.

APPLICATION Clients: In contrast to DEVICE clients, APPLICATION clients typi-cally subscribe to topics with high message volumes and always require persistent stor-age for offline message retrieval. This usage pattern aligns well with Kafka's architecture,

### Comparison with lightweight MQTT brokers

One of the key distinctions between TBMQ and lightweight MQTT brokers lies in its design focus. TBMQ is optimized for large-scale, cloud-based deployments where data durability, high availability, and throughput are critical. This contrasts with the light-weight edge brokers, such as Mosquitto or NanoMQ, which are optimized for resource-constrained environments like embedded devices or edge nodes.

Lightweight brokers typically prioritize low resource consumption and minimal over-head, often forgoing features like message durability and persistence to ensure fast per-formance with limited CPU, memory, and storage. These brokers are designed to run on devices with limited resources, providing basic message routing without the need for robust data storage or fault tolerance.

Thus, TBMQ should not be compared directly with lightweight brokers, as the oper-ational requirements they address are fundamentally different. While lightweight bro-kers serve small-scale, local deployments with limited resources, TBMQ is built for cloud-based, large-scale IoT systems where reliability, scalability, and data integrity are essential.

### Performance tests results overview

In the MQTT broker ecosystem, performance testing is an established practice among widely-used solutions. Many clustered MQTT brokers focus primarily on availability and performance, sometimes at the expense of communication integrity. The absence of persistence mechanisms in some brokers can result in message loss or failure to deliver messages to the intended recipients[36]. Our testing aims to contribute further insights into the broader evaluation of MQTT brokers, particularly in scenarios requiring mes-sage durability and scalability.

Given the diverse nature of IoT applications, were designed test scenarios that reflect real-world complexities and deployment environments. Beyond simply measuring scal-ability, our benchmarks evaluate the balance between vertical and horizontal scalability,offering a more comprehensive understanding of how TBMQ performs as resources and processing nodes increase.

To evaluate TBMQ's performance, we conducted two distinct tests, each designed to highlight specific aspects of its capabilities. These tests were performed using Amazon Web Services(AWS) infrastructure[37, 38], with TBMQ deployed using Kubernetes on AWS Elastic Kubernetes Service(EKS)[39, 40]. We selected AWS as the platform due to its widespread use in IoT backends and cloud-based MQTT deployments. This deployment approach ensures that the tests can be replicated on standard, widely avail-able hardware.

### Hardware used

 Table 2 presents the hardware specifications used for the 100 million MQTT connec-tions performance test.

The selection of AWS Graviton-based instances and the overall hardware configu-ration was directly aligned with the scale and nature of the tested scenario. Given the target of 100 million concurrent connections, we deployed 25 TBMQ nodes to ensure balanced load distribution and fault tolerance across the cluster. Each TBMQ node was responsible for managing approximately 4 million concurrent MQTT connections,a configuration chosen to maintain headroom for CPU and memory utilization while maximizing vertical resource usage per instance. The use of m6g.metal instances, each with 64 vCPUs and 256 GiB of RAM, provided sufficient computing capacity and high network throughput 25 Gibps per node- characteristics essential for handling large-scale concurrent sessions.

Kafka was deployed across nine m6a.2xlarge instances, evenly distributed across three AWS Availability Zones(three nodes per zone) to ensure high availability, fault isolation, and even partition distribution.

AWS Relational Database Service(RDS) has been deployed as a single instance of type db.m6i.large.

### Test methodology

IoT device profiles vary in terms of message frequency and payload size. For this test,we emulated smart tracker devices that transmit telemetry data containing five attrib-utes. Each PUBLISH message is approximately 114 bytes in size. An example payload is shown below:

$$
\begin{array}{l}{\{}\\ \text{" last":} 40.761894,\\ \text{" long":}-73.970455,\\ \text{" speed":} 55.5,\\ \text{" fuel":} 92,\\ \text{" batLvl":} 81\\ \end{array}
$$

The simulation involved 200,000 publisher clients organized into 500 groups, with each group generating 6,000 messages per second. Messages were published to uniquely structured topics using the pattern: CountryCode/RandomString/GroupId/ClientId, resulting in a total of 100 million distinct topic names. On the subscriber side, 500 persistent APPLICATION clients were configured- one per group- using topic filters of the form CountryCode/RandomString/GroupId/+ to match all publishers in their group.

This arrangement enabled each subscriber to receive 6,000 messages per second,resulting in a sustained system-wide throughput of 6 million messages per second. In this context, throughput includes both incoming messages published by clients and out-going messages delivered to subscribers. Throughout the test, the TBMQ cluster main-tained a total of 100,000,500 concurrent client sessions.

A dedicated test agent was responsible for orchestrating the provisioning and lifecycle of both publisher and subscriber MQTT clients. Publisher clients continuously streamed time-series data, while subscribers used topic filters to receive corresponding messages.

To ensure a stable test start, the system underwent a warm-up phase. Each pub-lisher sent one message in each of six iterations, resulting in 600 million warm-up messages generated over approximately seven minutes. This phase was essential for stabilizing message flow and initializing the system's data pipelines prior to the main testing window.

With the configuration of 500 APPLICATION subscribers, the data delivery and persistence layer operated solely through Kafka. Neither Redis nor PostgreSQL was actively involved in message handling during this test. The load on PostgreSQL remained minimal, limited to a small number of session and metadata operations per second, as the test focused exclusively on persistent APPLICATION clients that uti-lize Kafka-based topics for durable message delivery.

### Test summary

In TBMQ's architecture, all incoming MQTT PUBLISH messages are first routed through a shared Kafka topic named tbmq.msg.all, which decouples ingress pro-cessing from message dispatch. For this test, the topic was configured with 225 par-titions to support parallel ingestion across 25 TBMQ nodes. Each node processed messages from this topic using 9 dedicated Kafka consumer threads.

Since all 500 subscribers in this test were persistent APPLICATION clients, TBMQ also used dedicated per-client Kafka topics for durable delivery. Each topic followed the naming convention tbmq.msg.app.+{client_id} and was configured with a single partition,ensuring strict message ordering, isolation per subscriber.

Kafka producers were tuned for throughput using performance-optimized parame-ters such as increased buffer size, linger.ms, and lz4 compression. Table 3 summarizes

The test then continued for 24 h to monitor system stability and verify the absence of resource leaks or performance degradation over time. For reporting purposes, we selected a sample time window(from 5:00 PM to 5:50 PM) after all 100 million connec-tions had been established and the system reached steady-state operation. We chose a shorter time frame to present detailed monitoring data- such as CPU usage, memory load, and garbage collection- because showing the entire 24-hour period would have compressed the graphs, making important performance details difficult to read. The test was conducted using MQTT QoS level 1(AT_LEAST_ONCE) to guarantee that messages were delivered at least once, ensuring data reliability. Table 4 summarizes the key elements and results of the test.

### Comparative analysis of 100 M connection benchmarks

Although various performance benchmarks for MQTT brokers have been published,most of them evaluate single-node setups, often omitting persistence mechanisms or operating with transient client sessions[41]. These differences make direct comparison with our large-scale cluster tests unfeasible. The only comparable benchmark available is the EMQX 100 million connections test, which also focuses on validating broker sta-bility and resource utilization under extreme load with 100 million concurrently active connections[42].

We summarize both test scenarios in Table 5 and discuss the key distinctions in terms of connection handling, persistence, and architectural focus.

The presented comparison highlights two fundamentally different approaches to large-scale MQTT benchmarking. Both TBMQ and EMQX successfully demonstrated the ability to handle 100 million active connections with QoS 1. However, TBMQ achieved significantly higher total message throughput and superior efficiency in terms of throughput per vCPU- even when considering the additional resources required for its Kafka and PostgreSQL-backed persistence.

Moreover, TBMQ's architecture ensures cross-node session persistence through Kafka-backed storage, whereas EMQX employs node-local persistence, which may limit durability and failover support in clustered deployments.

### Performance test II: 3 M Msg/sec throughput with a single TBMQ node

The second test aimed to evaluate TBMQ's performance in processing and distributing MQTT messages using a single server node, as shown in figure 7.

### Hardware used

Table 6 provides the hardware specifications for the 3 million messages per second throughput test. The hardware configuration for this test was selected to reflect typi-cal production scenarios for edge or regional cloud deployments of high-throughput MQTT brokers.

The AWS instance type m7a.8xlarge, equipped with 32 vCPU and 128 GiB of RAM, was selected for this test. This instance belongs to the latest AMD-based family,optimized for general-purpose workloads with high network bandwidth. Such a configu-ration reflects a typical production deployment size, balancing vertical scaling poten-tial with high network throughput- essential for MQTT workloads requiring sustained message rates.

### Test methodology

To evaluate TBMQ's performance under fan-out(broadcast) MQTT communication pattern, we conducted a 30-minute benchmark using a compact but demanding deploy-ment. The test environment consisted of a single TBMQ node running in an AWS EKS cluster, accompanied by 3 Kafka brokers and a PostgreSQL instance provisioned via Amazon RDS.

The publisher setup included 100 MQTT publishers, each sending 10 messages per second. Messages were published to unique topics following the pattern Country-Code/City/ID, where ID is a unique identifier for each publisher. Each published message contained a payload of approximately 66 bytes, emulating lightweight telemetry typical of IoT sensors.

To assess message distribution efficiency, 3,000 subscriber clients were configured to subscribe using a shared topic filter: CountryCode/City/#. This allowed each sub-scriber to receive all messages from all publishers, simulating a high-volume broadcast scenario with a total downstream delivery rate of 3 million messages per second.

The test aimed to evaluate whether TBMQ could maintain stable throughput and low latency under a continuous, high-volume fan-out workload, while avoiding resource bot-tlenecks such as memory pressure or CPU saturation.

### Test summary

In accordance with TBMQ's message routing architecture, all MQTT PUBLISH mes-sages routed through the shared Kafka topic tbmq.msg.all This topic is used for for-warding messages regardless of subscriber type unless durable delivery for persistent DEVICE clients is explicitly required.

In this test, all 3,000 subscribers were non-persistent clients subscribed to a shared topic filter. Therefore, no per-client Kafka topics were involved.

The tbmq.msg.all topic was configured with 6 partitions, and the TBMQ node was set up with 6 dedicated Kafka consumer threads to maximize processing parallelism.Kafka consumer settings were tuned for efficiency, including fetch.min.bytes:128, to reduce overhead during message polling under consistent high-throughput conditions.

Producer-side Kafka settings were left at near-default values. Specifically, linger.ms was not configured, batch.size was explicitly set to 512 bytes(lower than Kafka's default), and compression.type was left as none. These settings reflect an intention-ally conservative configuration, since the test focused on fan-out delivery throughput with a low number of publishers, where high batching efficiency was not required.

Topic-level configuration for tbmq.msg.all followed TBMQ's default settings and was not modified for this test. Only consumer and producer parameters were explicitly tuned, as summarized in Table 7.

This setup allowed a single TBMQ node to handle a fan-out throughput of 3 million messages per second efficiently, with predictable performance and resource usage.

TBMQ processed a throughput of 3 million messages per second using a single node,highlighting its efficiency in high-load scenarios. The test ran for 30 min and demon-strated an average message latency of 7.4 ms, which indicates TBMQ's ability to manage large message volumes while maintaining low latency.

During the evaluation process, various instance types were tested before settling on the m7a.8xlarge as the optimal choice for TBMQ. Notably, the smaller m7a.4xlarge instance with 16 vCPU and 64GiB RAM also delivered solid performance, maintaining an average message latency of 14.2 ms at 90% CPU utilization.

These findings highlight the flexibility and scalability of TBMQ, demonstrating its capability to achieve high throughput and low latency even on smaller hardware con-figurations. Table 8 summarizes the key elements and results of the test.

### Comparison with open-source MQTT benchmarks

While several open-source MQTT benchmarks have explored fan-out and high-throughput messaging scenarios[41], direct quantitative comparison remains challeng-ing due to differences in test configurations, particularly regarding QoS levels, payload sizes, and the lack of disclosed hardware specifications in those studies. Recent stud-ies have further highlighted variability in performance and resource usage across open-source MQTT brokers, including differences in how they handle QoS levels and client state management[43].

Unlike previously published benchmarks, this test provides a transparent evaluation of TBMQ's fan-out performance under clearly defined conditions- including hard-ware setup, QoS level, and system resource usage-enabling a reproducible and realistic assessment of broker performance. These results position TBMQ among the few MQTT brokers capable of sustaining multi-million message-per-second fan-out rates on a single production-grade instance.

### Real-world deployments

The experiments and messaging patterns presented in this study were directly informed by feedback and architectural requirements from real-world IoT deploy-ments. While specific client identities cannot be disclosed due to non-disclosure agreements(NDAs), the following two anonymized scenarios illustrate how TBMQ is applied in production at scale- and how its architectural features address critical messaging needs such as data durability, session persistence, and scalable routing.

● Large-scale retail telemetry system One deployment involves over 500,000 telem-etry sensors across more than 10,000 retail locations operated by a major Euro-pean retailer. Each location hosts one or more custom MQTT gateways that aggregate sensor data- such as temperature, humidity, door status, and HVAC metrics- from refrigeration units, energy meters, and other in-store systems.Sensors report data at configurable intervals, and MQTT is used to deliver these

readings to backend systems using persistent sessions. This ensures durable mes-sage delivery even under intermittent network conditions. The MQTT broker must support high fan-in throughput from geographically distributed locations and reliably forward messages to downstream analytics and alerting services. This deployment highlights the importance of horizontal scalability and lossless deliv-ery guarantees, particularly for persistent APPLICATION clients subscribing to high-throughput upstream data streams- a pattern directly aligned with Perfor-mance Test I.

● Utility-grade IoT metering and alerting system Another production deployment is operated by a national LoRaWAN infrastructure provider, covering tens of thousands of water meters across 50+ municipalities. Devices report consumption data on an hourly basis using MQTT-over-gateway connections. Reported values are cumula-tive, and deltas are computed on the backend to derive hourly and daily usage sta-tistics. The data is processed in real time by analytics systems acting as persistent APPLICATION clients, which also perform anomaly detection(e.g., leak detec-tion, high flow, or no-flow alerts). Depending on customer type and alert severity,downstream systems trigger notifications or control actions. In addition to telemetry ingestion, the system supports broadcasting control messages- such as configura-tion updates, alert thresholds, or firmware scheduling- to large groups of devices via shared topic filters. These fan-out interactions are published by a backend service and received in parallel by many devices. This operational model mirrors the fan-out messaging pattern evaluated in Performance Test II.

Together, these two deployments demonstrate TBMQ's practical value in supporting durable, scalable, and adaptive MQTT communication across different IoT infrastruc-tures-from retail environments to municipal utilities.

### Discussion

This article has evaluated TBMQ in detail, demonstrating its capabilities as an MQTT broker, particularly suited for large-scale IoT applications. TBMQ has been developed with a strong focus on the specific demands of IoT ecosystems, prioritizing scalability,fault tolerance, and data durability.

The categorization of MQTT clients into DEVICE and APPLICATION types allows TBMQ to address different operational requirements effectively. This classification optimizes message processing and storage, contributing to overall system efficiency.Additionally, TBMQ's open-source framework fosters community involvement, facili-tating ongoing innovation and the potential establishment of new standards in IoT communications.

While TBMQ demonstrates strong architectural characteristics and high perfor-mance, several opportunities remain for further optimization, feature expansion, and architectural exploration. These include improvements to session and memory manage-ment, protocol support, and evaluation of alternative technologies that may be applica-ble in specific deployment contexts:

● After migrating persistent DEVICE message storage from PostgreSQL to Redis in TBMQ v2.0, we significantly improved the broker's ability to handle high-through-put message persistence for persistent DEVICE clients. While TBMQ stores cli-ent sessions and subscription data in memory and uses Redis as a caching layer for various system data objects, PostgreSQL remains the primary persistence store for session-related metadata- such as client session context, pending message state,and shared subscription information. As part of future work, TBMQ team plan to explore offloading this session-related metadata entirely to Redis or other in-memory data stores, to further improve overall system performance and reduce PostgreSQL involvement in session management operations. This would allow PostgreSQL to focus exclusively on managing user accounts, MQTT client credentials, and general broker configuration data.

● TBMQ currently stores client sessions and subscription data in memory, which increases RAM usage, as each node in the cluster maintains a local copy. Another aspect for future work is to explore various approaches for optimizing session and subscription data handling in clustered deployments. This includes introducing deterministic client session sharding based on partitioning strategies like consistent hashing, applying session affinity mechanisms within node groups, and evaluating techniques for managing shared subscriptions efficiently- either by grouping sub-scribers within the same node group or coordinating delivery across node groups when needed. The objective is to identify the most effective combination of tech-niques and algorithms that minimize memory footprint and coordination overhead while preserving TBMQ's high-throughput performance.

● TBMQ, as a newer broker, does not currently support MQTT-SN- a protocol designed for lightweight communication with resource-constrained devices. As part of future development, the TBMQ team is exploring a gateway-based integration approach, where a dedicated component handles MQTT-SN communication and translates it to standard MQTT for seamless forwarding into TBMQ. This design would ensure protocol compatibility while preserving deployment flexibility and sys-tem scalability.

● TBMQ already supports integration with external systems through a dedicated microservice called the TBMQ Integration Executor. This component currently ena-bles communication with HTTP endpoints, Kafka brokers, and other MQTT bro-kers. Future work will focus on extending this integration layer to support a broader set of protocols and systems, enhancing TBMQ's applicability across diverse IoT architectures.

● Future work will also include a more comprehensive evaluation of TBMQ's latency behavior under diverse operational conditions. This includes testing under varying QoS levels for different MQTT communication patterns, intermittent connectiv-ity, fluctuating client loads, and network jitter. Such scenarios would help to further characterize TBMQ's responsiveness and reliability under real-world constraints.

. While Kafka is currently a central component in TBMQ's architecture due to its proven durability and throughput characteristics, future work may include an inves tigation of alternative event streaming technologies such as NATS[44].

### Conclusion

TBMQ's use of technologies such as Netty and Kafka demonstrates its ability to manage a large number of concurrent client connections and handle significant message volumes effectively. The broker's architecture is designed to maintain strong performance during periods of high load while ensuring continuous system operation and data integrity in various deployment scenarios.

Compared to existing open-source MQTT brokers, TBMQ offers a unique combina-tion of critical capabilities-including durable message storage, persistent session han-dling, fault-tolerant clustering, and efficient handling of core MQTT communication patterns. These advantages, along with cloud-native deployment support and high CPU efficiency,make TBMQ particularly well-suited for demanding IoT applications at scale.

The performance tests presented in this study offer valuable insights into TBMQ's capabilities, illustrating that it is well-suited to meet the demanding requirements of modern IoT environments.

In conclusion, TBMQ provides a reliable and efficient MQTT broker solution capable of addressing the challenges posed by large-scale IoT deployments. The development of TBMQ integrates practical industry knowledge with modern technological approaches,positioning it as a relevant solution in the IoT and MQTT broker landscape. As the IoT ecosystem continues to evolve, TBMQ is expected to support scalable and dependable communication across complex device networks.

Future development will focus on further reducing PostgreSQL involvement by off-loading session-related metadata to Redis or alternative in-memory data stores. The team also aims to introduce deterministic client session sharding and improve the effi-ciency of subscription handling to lower memory usage in clustered deployments. Sup-port for MQTT-SN is planned through a gateway-based integration strategy that is better suited for constrained devices. In addition, upcoming work will expand the bro-ker's integration capabilities to support a wider range of external systems. There are also plans to extend performance evaluation under variable network conditions, different QoS levels, and fluctuating client loads to better understand system behavior in realistic environments.
